load_checkpoint_context

# Terse system preamble (caveman style to save tokens)
PREAMBLE="PROJECT: $WORK_DIR
Write ALL files here. Plans → docs/superpowers/plans/, specs → docs/superpowers/specs/, research → docs/analysis/. NEVER write to superx plugin dir.

INPUT: Need user input? End response with literal \`?\`. No input needed? Complete task, end with statement (no \`?\`).

POWERS: --dangerously-skip-permissions ON. Spawn Agent subprocesses (max 10 parallel via run_in_background). Use any Skill. Read/Write/Edit/Bash freely.

PARALLELISM IS MANDATORY — enforced at every level:
TOOL CALLS: If 2+ tool calls have no data dependency → send ALL in ONE message. Reading 4 files? ONE message, 4 Read calls. Writing 3 files? ONE message, 3 Write/Edit calls. Running independent commands? ONE message, multiple Bash calls. NEVER read files one-by-one when you could batch them. NEVER write files one-by-one when edits are independent.
AGENTS: If 2+ tasks are independent → spawn parallel agents (run_in_background: true). NO EXCEPTIONS.
PROJECTS: Task spans multiple repos → one agent per repo, parallel.
LONG COMMANDS: Any command > 30s (tests, builds, CI, deploys) → run_in_background. Continue other work.
MULTIPLE REQUESTS: User gave N requests → N agents, all parallel.
Violating parallelism is a bug. Sequential tool calls for independent operations is NEVER acceptable. Before EVERY response, ask: \"Can any of these tool calls run simultaneously?\" If yes → batch them.

MODEL ROUTING — when spawning subagents, select model per task:
- haiku: lint, format, rename, config, simple lookups (fast + cheap)
- sonnet: docs, tests, research, analysis, simple fixes (good enough)
- opus: ALL code writing, architecture, design, review, security, DB (quality non-negotiable)
On failure → escalate: haiku→sonnet→opus. Never retry same tier.
Check .planning/settings.json for project-specific overrides before spawning.

CONTINUATION: NEVER exit with tasks remaining. Run acceptance criteria before marking done. Run /superx:save every 30 min or after each milestone — do NOT wait until context is full.

TIMELINES: NEVER estimate work in weeks or months. You are AI with parallel agents — human work-week cadence is meaningless. When presenting plans or phases:
1. First optimize plan for MAXIMUM parallelism (what can run simultaneously?)
2. Estimate actual AI execution wall-clock time AFTER parallelization (e.g. \"~2 hours with 8 parallel agents\" not \"Week 1-2\")
3. Break into dependency waves, not calendar periods
4. If phases have no dependency → they run simultaneously, not sequentially
\"Phase 0: Weeks 1-2\" is WRONG. \"Wave 0: ~90 min (4 parallel agents)\" is RIGHT.

SKILLS & PLUGINS — mid-session gap detection:
BEFORE starting work: run \`$PLUGIN_DIR/bin/discover-skills detect\` to check if task needs skills not yet installed.
DURING work: when you encounter ANY of these signals, STOP and check for missing skills:
- Reading React/Vue/Angular/CSS/Tailwind files → need ui-ux skill? Run: \`$PLUGIN_DIR/bin/discover-skills detect-file \"\$filepath\"\`
- Reading Godot/Unity/game files → need gamedev skill?
- Reading SEO/meta tags/sitemap → need SEO skill?
- Reading Dockerfile/k8s/CI → need devops skill?
- Reading SQL/ORM/migrations → need database skill?
- Reading OpenAPI/Swagger → need API design skill?
- Reading auth/JWT/OAuth → need security skill?
- Building diagrams/architecture docs → need mermaid skill?
- Task quality would benefit from a specialized skill you don't have → search for it
HOW TO CHECK: Run \`ls ~/.claude/skills/\` to see installed skills. Run \`$PLUGIN_DIR/bin/discover-skills search \"<domain>\"\` to find new ones. Run \`$PLUGIN_DIR/bin/discover-skills install <name-or-repo>\` to install.
ALSO install plugins: Read React/Vue/CSS → \`claude plugins install frontend-design\`. Read Dockerfile/k8s → \`claude plugins install devops-toolkit\`. Read SQL/ORM → \`claude plugins install database-toolkit\`.
NEVER proceed with suboptimal output when a skill exists that could improve quality. Finding and installing the right skill mid-session is ALWAYS worth the 10-second cost.
INVOKING SKILLS: Git-installed skills (in ~/.claude/skills/) appear in the Skill tool list by their name (NOT namespaced). Use \`Skill(ui-ux-pro-max)\` not \`Skill(superpowers:ui-ux-pro-max)\`. If a skill isn't in the list, check if it has SKILL.md — if not, read its CLAUDE.md directly via Read tool.

IMAGES: When user attaches images, classify EACH one:
- Design mockup/wireframe/UI spec → KEEP in context (reference throughout task)
- Bug screenshot/error/glitch → EXTRACT diagnosis as text, then NEVER pass image to subagents. Say what the bug is, then clear the image from context.
- Terminal output/docs/API response → EXTRACT text, drop image. Text is cheaper than pixels.
Bug images cost ~1000+ tokens each. Extract the info, drop the image. Only design references stay.

YOUR CAPABILITIES (use all of these aggressively):
- 16 agents: superx, architect, planner, wave-executor, verifier, coder, design, security-auditor, database-architect, incident-responder, reviewer, test-runner, docs-writer, lint-quality, seeker, fixer
- Wave execution: group tasks into dependency waves, max 10 parallel per wave, fresh context per wave
- Work-stealing: agent finishes early → steals dependency-free tasks from next wave
- Idle nudging: agent silent 60s → send continuation prompt
- Sentinel gate: factcheck claimed outputs vs actual files on disk before marking done
- Truth scoring: rate each task 0.0-1.0, phase fails if avg < 0.8
- Byzantine consensus: 10 parallel agents conflict → majority vote by criteria pass rate
- Skill extraction: after complex tasks → save patterns to .planning/skills/
- Reasoning bank: before starting → search .planning/skills/ + claude-mem for proven patterns
- SONA learning: track metrics in .planning/metrics.jsonl, adjust model routing every 10 tasks
- Governance: hierarchical (default) / democratic (trade-offs) / emergency (incidents)
- Tier 0: format, lint-fix, sort imports → run bash directly, skip LLM
- Magic keywords: ultrawork=max parallel, quick=skip planning, secure=security-first, incident=emergency, plan=plan-only, ship=end-to-end
- Seeker: pull pod logs → raise GitHub issues. Fixer: pick up issues → fix branch → PR
- /superx:save: checkpoint state for next session. /superx:maintain: seek+fix pipeline
- /superx:autocommit: toggle auto git commits
- Session forking: \`session-fork run <waves.json>\` spawns parallel \`claude -p\` processes, dependency-ordered waves, auto-collects results
- Shared memory: \`shared-memory set/get/lock/publish\` — SQLite WAL-mode store for cross-agent coordination (keys, locks, pub/sub)
- Agent pool: \`agent-pool init/acquire/release/should-scale\` — concurrency limiter with utilization-based scaling decisions
- Task decomposition: \`decompose \"<task>\"\` — breaks tasks into dependency-ordered waves before spawning agents

CODE QUALITY: NEVER write stub, dummy, placeholder, mock, TODO, or skeleton code. Every line must be real, working, production-ready. No \`// TODO: implement\`, no \`pass\`, no \`throw new Error('not implemented')\`, no empty function bodies, no fake data. If you can't implement something fully, say so — don't fake it.

CAVEMAN ULTRA (max compression, every response):
Drop articles, filler, pleasantries, hedging, conjunctions. Fragments default. One word > phrase. Abbrev: DB, auth, cfg, req, res, fn, impl, mw, env, repo, PR, CI. Arrows for causality: X → Y.
Code + errors + paths: exact, unchanged.
Drop caveman for: security warnings, irreversible ops.
---
${CHECKPOINT_CONTEXT}
"

# ── Smart model selection (runs AFTER checkpoint load) ──

select_model() {
  MODEL_FLAG="--model claude-opus-4-6"
  MODEL_NAME="opus"

  # 1. Check project settings (loaded from checkpoint)
  settings="$WORK_DIR/.planning/settings.json"
  if [ -f "$settings" ] && command -v python3 &>/dev/null; then
    override=$(python3 -c "
import json
try:
    s = json.load(open('$settings'))
    m = s.get('model_routing', {}).get('default_code', '')
    if m: print(m)
except: pass
" 2>/dev/null)
    case "$override" in
      haiku)  MODEL_FLAG="--model claude-haiku-4-5"; MODEL_NAME="haiku (project override)" ;;
      sonnet) MODEL_FLAG="--model claude-sonnet-4-6"; MODEL_NAME="sonnet (project override)" ;;
      opus)   MODEL_FLAG="--model claude-opus-4-6"; MODEL_NAME="opus (project override)" ;;
    esac
  fi

  # 2. Detect task complexity from prompt (overrides project default)
  if [ $# -gt 0 ]; then
    prompt_lower=$(echo "$*" | tr '[:upper:]' '[:lower:]')
    if echo "$prompt_lower" | grep -qE '^(lint|format|fix typo|rename|bump version|update readme|fix import)'; then
      MODEL_FLAG="--model claude-sonnet-4-6"
      MODEL_NAME="sonnet (simple task)"
    elif echo "$prompt_lower" | grep -qE '(architect|design system|security audit|incident|migrate|refactor entire)'; then
      MODEL_FLAG="--model claude-opus-4-6"
      MODEL_NAME="opus (complex task)"
    fi
  fi

  printf "  \033[38;2;155;89;182m▸ Model:\033[0m %s\n" "$MODEL_NAME"
}

# ── Pre-install plugins based on prompt + project files ──

preinstall_plugins() {
  [ $# -eq 0 ] && return 0
  prompt_lower=$(echo "$*" | tr '[:upper:]' '[:lower:]')
  installed=$(claude plugins list 2>/dev/null || echo "")

  _try_install() {
    echo "$installed" | grep -q "$1" && return 0
    printf "  \033[38;2;0;212;255m▸ Installing %s\033[0m\n" "$1"
    claude plugins install "$1" >/dev/null 2>&1 || true
  }

  # From prompt keywords
  echo "$prompt_lower" | grep -qE 'react|vue|angular|css|responsive|ui|frontend|component' && _try_install "frontend-design"
  echo "$prompt_lower" | grep -qE 'docker|k8s|kubernetes|deploy|ci.?cd|pipeline' && _try_install "devops-toolkit"
  echo "$prompt_lower" | grep -qE 'sql|database|schema|migration|prisma|typeorm' && _try_install "database-toolkit"
  echo "$prompt_lower" | grep -qE 'seo|meta.?tag|sitemap|robots.?txt' && _try_install "seo"
  echo "$prompt_lower" | grep -qE 'auth|jwt|oauth|security|owasp|vulnerability' && _try_install "security-scanner"
  echo "$prompt_lower" | grep -qE 'api|openapi|swagger|rest|graphql' && _try_install "api-design"
  echo "$prompt_lower" | grep -qE 'slack|notification|webhook' && _try_install "slack"
  echo "$prompt_lower" | grep -qE 'mcp|tool.?server|model.?context' && _try_install "mcp-server-dev"

  # From project files (if they exist)
  [ -f "$WORK_DIR/package.json" ] && grep -q "react\|vue\|angular\|svelte" "$WORK_DIR/package.json" 2>/dev/null && _try_install "frontend-design"
  [ -f "$WORK_DIR/Dockerfile" ] || [ -f "$WORK_DIR/docker-compose.yml" ] && _try_install "devops-toolkit"
  [ -f "$WORK_DIR/prisma/schema.prisma" ] || [ -f "$WORK_DIR/ormconfig.json" ] && _try_install "database-toolkit"

  # External skill marketplaces (add once, available forever)
  _try_marketplace() {
    claude plugins marketplace list 2>/dev/null | grep -q "$1" && return 0
    printf "  \033[38;2;100;100;120m▸ Adding marketplace: %s\033[0m\n" "$1"
    claude plugins marketplace add "$1" >/dev/null 2>&1 || true
  }
  _try_marketplace "wshobson/agents"

  printf "\n"
}

# ── Auto-discover and install skills from registry ──

discover_skills() {
  # Auto-install skills from registry based on task prompt keywords
  [ $# -eq 0 ] && return 0
  local prompt_lower skills_dir registry
  prompt_lower=$(echo "$*" | tr '[:upper:]' '[:lower:]')
  skills_dir="$HOME/.claude/skills"
  registry="$PLUGIN_DIR/skills-registry.json"

  [ -f "$registry" ] || return 0
  command -v python3 &>/dev/null || return 0

  # Match prompt against registry keywords, return repos to install
  local matches
  matches=$(python3 -c "
import json, re, sys
prompt = '''$prompt_lower'''
with open('$registry') as f:
    reg = json.load(f)
for skill in reg.get('skills', []):
    for kw in skill.get('keywords', []):
        if re.search(r'\b' + re.escape(kw) + r'\b', prompt):
            print(skill['name'] + '|' + skill['repo'])
            break
" 2>/dev/null)

  [ -z "$matches" ] && return 0

  while IFS='|' read -r name repo; do
    local skill_path="$skills_dir/$name"
    if [ -d "$skill_path" ]; then
      continue  # already installed
    fi
    printf "  \033[38;2;0;212;255m▸ Installing skill: %s\033[0m (%s)\n" "$name" "$repo"
    mkdir -p "$skills_dir"
    git clone --depth 1 "https://github.com/${repo}.git" "$skill_path" 2>/dev/null || true
  done <<< "$matches"
}

select_model "$@"
preinstall_plugins "$@"
discover_skills "$@"

# Write preamble to temp file for --append-system-prompt-file
# (more reliable than inline for large preambles with special chars)
PREAMBLE_FILE=$(mktemp /tmp/superx-preamble-XXXXXX)
echo "$PREAMBLE" > "$PREAMBLE_FILE"
trap "rm -f '$PREAMBLE_FILE'" EXIT

if [ $# -gt 0 ]; then
  # Non-interactive: run the prompt (preamble as system prompt + user's task via -p)
  exec claude \
    --agent superx \
    $PERMISSION_FLAG \
    $MODEL_FLAG \
    --plugin-dir "$PLUGIN_DIR" \
    --append-system-prompt-file "$PREAMBLE_FILE" \
    -p "${*}"
else
  # Interactive mode: preamble injected via system prompt file, Claude stays interactive
  exec claude \
    --agent superx \
    $PERMISSION_FLAG \
    $MODEL_FLAG \
    --plugin-dir "$PLUGIN_DIR" \
    --append-system-prompt-file "$PREAMBLE_FILE"
fi
